Problem Statement 3 — AI-Driven Threat Detection & Simulation Engine
Hack Malenadu '26 | Cybersecurity Track
🏢 Context
Organizations face an ever-expanding cybersecurity threat surface — from
sophisticated APTs (Advanced Persistent Threats) to insider threats and zero-day
exploits. Traditional rule-based detection systems are too slow, too brittle, and too
reactive: they catch known patterns, miss novel attacks, and overwhelm security
teams with undifferentiated alerts. The industry urgently needs AI systems that
detect, explain, and simulate — enabling security teams to shift from reactive
firefighting to proactive defence.
🧩 Problem Statement
Build an AI-driven Threat Detection & Simulation Engine that analyzes signals
across network, endpoint, and application layers to detect anomalous and malicious
patterns in real time, classifies threats with explainability, and generates actionable
simulation-based prevention playbooks — helping security teams understand not
just that a threat exists, but why it was flagged and what to do before the next one
hits.
The core challenge: security data is high-volume, high-noise, and adversarial.
Attackers deliberately craft patterns to evade detection. Your system must be robust,
explainable, and useful to a real SOC (Security Operations Center) analyst — not
just technically impressive on clean data.
🔍 Scope & Complexity Requirements
Layer 1 — Multi-Signal Ingestion & Normalization
● Ingest and correlate signals from at least two of the three layers:
o Network layer: simulated network flow logs (src/dst IP, port, protocol,
bytes, duration, flags)
o Endpoint layer: simulated process execution logs (process name,
parent PID, user, file access, registry changes)
o Application layer: simulated HTTP/API logs (method, endpoint, status
code, payload size, user agent, geolocation)
● Normalize heterogeneous log formats into a unified event schema before
analysis
● Handle high-throughput ingestion: your system should not break or stall
under a burst of 500+ events/second in simulation
Layer 2 — Threat Detection with Classification
● Detect and classify at least four distinct threat categories:
o Brute force / credential stuffing — repeated failed authentication
from single or distributed sources
o Lateral movement — unusual internal traffic patterns between
endpoints after initial compromise
o Data exfiltration — abnormally large or frequent outbound data
transfers to external destinations
o Command & Control (C2) beaconing — periodic, low-volume
connections to external IPs at regular intervals
● Assign a confidence score and severity level (Low / Medium / High /
Critical) to each detected event
● Correlate events across layers — a single alert from one layer is noise; the
same behavior appearing across network + endpoint layers simultaneously is
a high-confidence incident
📦 Data Considerations
● Use publicly available security datasets: CICIDS, KDD Cup 99, UNSW-NB15,
or generate synthetic logs
● Synthetic data must include both benign and malicious traffic — your
detection model must learn to distinguish between them
● Seed your demo dataset with at least two active attack scenarios running
simultaneously (e.g., a brute force attempt + a C2 beacon)
● Include a realistic false positive in your demo data — a legitimate admin
performing bulk file transfers that superficially resembles exfiltration
